window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2017>1>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2017","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : PERIOD, FREQUENCY AND AMPLITUDE OF A BODY EXECUTING S.H.M","question":"You are provided with two retort stands, two-metre rules, pieces of thread and other necessary apparatus.    (i) Set up the apparatus as illustrated above ensuring the strings are permanently 10 cm from either end of the rule.  (ii) Measure and record the length  L  = 80 cm of the two strings.  (iii) Hold both ends of the rule and displace the rule slightly, then release so that it oscillates about a vertical axis through its centre.  (iv) Determine and record the time  t for 10 complete oscillations.  (v) Determine the period  T  of oscillations.  (vi) Evaluate log  T  and  L .  (vii) Repeat the procedure for four other values of  L  = 70 cm, 60 cm, 50 cm, and 40 cm  (viii) Tabulate your readings.  (ix) Plot a graph with log  T on the vertical axis and log  L on the horizontal axis.  (x) Determine the slope,  s , and the intercept,  c on the vertical axis.  (xi) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"S/N L(cm) t(s) T = t10\\frac{t}{10}10t\u200blog T log L1 80.0 17.90 1.79 0.252 1.9032 70.0 17.30 1.73 0.238 1.8453 60.0 15.34 1.53 0.185 1.7754 50.0 13.90 1.39 0.145 1.6985 40.0 13.06 1.31 0.155 1.602        (x)s=\u2206log T\u2206log L=log T2 - log T1log L2 - log L1    = 0.245\u22120.1551.9\u22121.65\\frac{0.245-0.155}{1.9-1.65}1.9\u22121.650.245\u22120.155\u200b = 0.090.25\\frac{0.09}{0.25}0.250.09\u200b = 0.36    To get the equation of the line (y = mx + c):    y - 0.245 = 0.36(x - 1.90)    y - 0.245 = 0.36x - 0.684    y = 0.36x - 0.439    \u2234 c = -0.439     Precautions:     1. I avoided parallax errors while taking readings from the metre rule and stopwatch by ensuring my eyes were at the correct angle.    2. I ensured that the support of the bifilar pendulum was rigid to prevent unnecessary vibrations or distortions during the experiment.    3. I checked that the strings of the pendulum were of equal length and securely fastened to maintain symmetry and accuracy in oscillations.    4. I ensured that the pendulum oscillated smoothly and regularly in a horizontal plane to minimize external interference and ensure consistent results.    5. I verified that the strings were free from tangling or twisting, which could disrupt the motion of the pendulum.    6. I repeated the experiment multiple times to reduce random errors and improve reliability.    7. I avoided sudden movements or air disturbances near the setup, ensuring stable conditions for the experiment.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2017>1>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2017","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION (S.H.M)","question":"Define simple harmonic motion.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Simple Harmonic Motion (SHM) is a type of periodic motion in which an object moves back and forth along a straight line such that its acceleration is directly proportional to its displacement from a fixed equilibrium position and is always directed towards that position. Mathematically, it can be expressed as:    a = \u2212\u03c92x    Where:  a is the acceleration,  \u03c9 is the angular frequency,  x is the displacement from equilibrium.    This restoring force ensures that the object oscillates in a regular and repeating cycle, characteristic of SHM, such as in the motion of a pendulum or a vibrating spring.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2017>1>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2017","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : PERIOD, FREQUENCY AND AMPLITUDE OF A BODY EXECUTING S.H.M","question":"Determine the value of  L  corresponding to  t  = 12 s from the graph in 1 (a).    (Provide your answer to 2 d.p e.g 123.123 Js)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"When t = 12 s,    T = t10\\frac{t}{10}10t\u200b = 1210\\frac{12}{10}1012\u200b = 1.2    log T = log 1.2 = 0.079    From the graph, log L = 1.45 when log T = 0.079    L = 101.45    \u2234 L = 28.18 cm","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2017>2>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2017","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : EVAPORATION AND BOILING","question":"You are provided with a beaker, a thermometer, a stirrer, Stopwatch/clock, measuring cylinder, table salt, water, and other necessary materials.  (i) You Measure 200 cm  of water into the beaker.  (ii) Heat the water until it boils steadily for about 2 minutes.  (iii) Read and record the boiling point  b0 .  (iv)  Add table salt of mass  M  = 10.0 g to the boiling water and stir continuously until another boiling point  b  is attained.  (v) Read and record  bi .  (vi) Evaluate \u03b8 = (bi - b0 )  (vii) Using the same mixture, repeat the procedure four more times by adding 10.0 g of salt each time to give the cumulative mass  Mi  of salt as 20 g, 30 g, 40 g, and 50 g.  (viii) In each case allow the mixture to boil steadily for  at least 2 minutes then read and record the boiling point  b .   (ix) Tabulate your readings.  (x) Plot a graph with  Mi  on the vertical axis and  \u03b8i on the horizontal axis.  (xi) Determine the slope, s, of the graph.  (xii) State  two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"bo = 102\u00b0C    S/N M/g bi/ \u00b0C \u03b8i = (bi - bo)/ \u00b0C1.0 10.0 104 22.0 20.0 106 43.0 30.0 108 64.0 40.0 110 85.0 50.0 112 10        (xi) s = \u2206M\u2206\u03b8\\frac{\u2206M}{\u2206\u03b8}\u2206\u03b8\u2206M\u200b = M2\u2212M1\u03b82\u2212\u03b81\\frac{M_{2}-M_{1}}{\u03b8_{2}-\u03b8_{1}}\u03b82\u200b\u2212\u03b81\u200bM2\u200b\u2212M1\u200b\u200b = 50\u22121010\u22122\\frac{50-10}{10-2}10\u2212250\u221210\u200b = 408\\frac{40}{8}840\u200b = 5     Precautions:     1. I stirred the water gently and consistently to ensure a uniform distribution of heat throughout the liquid.    2. I avoided splashing to prevent heat loss and ensure accurate measurements of the water's mass and temperature.    3. I eliminated parallax errors by aligning my eye level with the scale on the thermometer and stop clock during readings.    4. I ensured the thermometer bulb was fully immersed without touching the container's bottom or sides for accurate temperature readings.    5. I repeated the experiment multiple times to ensure reliability and reduce the impact of random errors.      6. I used clean and dry equipment to avoid contamination or changes in the water's thermal properties.    7. I minimized external air movement and heat sources near the setup to maintain consistent environmental conditions.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2017>2>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2017","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : BOILING POINT","question":"Define the boiling point of a liquid.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The boiling point of a liquid is the temperature at which its vapor pressure equals the external atmospheric pressure, causing the liquid to transition into a gaseous state throughout its volume. At this temperature, the molecules of the liquid have enough energy to overcome intermolecular forces and escape as vapor.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2017>2>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2017","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : BOILING POINT","question":"What effects do impurities have on the boiling point of a liquid?","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Impurities generally elevate the boiling point of a liquid. This occurs because impurities disrupt the liquid's molecular arrangement, making it more difficult for molecules to escape into the gas phase. Consequently, a higher temperature is required to overcome the increased intermolecular forces and achieve boiling. This phenomenon is known as boiling point elevation.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2017>3>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2017","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"You are provided with cells, a potentiometer, an ammeter, a voltmeter, a bulb, a key, a jockey, and other necessary materials.    (i) Measure and record the e.m.f  E of the battery.  (ii) Set up a circuit as shown in the diagram above.  (iii) Close the key  K and use the jockey to make a firm contact at  J on the potentiometer wire such that PJ =  x  = 10 cm.  (iv) Take and record the voltmeter reading V and the corresponding ammeter reading I.  (v) Evaluate log  V and log  I .  (vi) Repeat the procedure for five other values of  x  = 20 cm, 30 cm, 40 cm, 50 cm, and 60 cm.  (vii) Tabulate your readings.  (viii) Plot a graph with log  I on the vertical axis and log  V on the horizontal axis.  (ix) Determine the slope  s , of the graph.  (x) Determine the intercept,  c , on the vertical axis.  (xi) State  two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"E = 3.0 V    S/Nx(cm)V(V)I(A)log Vlog I110.00.190.10-0.721-1.000220.00.330.12-0.482-0.921330.00.470.14-0.328-0.854440.00.650.15-0.187-0.824550.00.820.16-0.086-0.796660.00.960.17-0.018-0.770        (ix)s=\u2206log I\u2206log V=log I2 - log l1log V2 - log V1  = \u22120.775\u2212\u22120.9\u22120.025\u2212\u22120.425\\frac{-0.775--0.9}{-0.025--0.425}\u22120.025\u2212\u22120.425\u22120.775\u2212\u22120.9\u200b = 0.1250.4\\frac{0.125}{0.4}0.40.125\u200b = 0.31     Precautions:     1. I avoided parallax errors by ensuring my eye was level with the scale while taking readings from the ammeter and voltmeter to improve accuracy.    2. I opened the key when readings were not being taken to prevent unnecessary current flow, ensuring the cells did not run down prematurely.    3. I avoided dragging the jockey along the potentiometer wire to prevent damage to the wire and maintain consistent resistance throughout its length.    4. I checked that all connections were secure and free from corrosion to prevent fluctuations in current or voltage.    5. I ensured the potentiometer wire was straight and taut to avoid inconsistencies in resistance measurements.    6. I repeated the measurements multiple times to reduce random errors and improve the reliability of the data.    7. I calibrated the instruments before use to detect and correct any zero errors in the measuring devices.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2017>3>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2017","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE AND ELECTRIC CURRENT","question":"How is the brightness of the bulb affected as  x  increases? Give a reason for your answer.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"As x increases, the brightness of the bulb increases. As x increases, the brightness of the bulb increases because the voltage across the bulb increases. This happens when x corresponds to a condition where the bulb is positioned or connected to experience a greater share of the supplied voltage, resulting in more current flowing through it.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2017>3>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2017","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CONDUCTION THROUGH MATERIALS","question":"List two electrical devices whose actions do not obey Ohm's law.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Here are several electrical devices whose actions do not obey Ohm's law:    1. Diodes: These include light-emitting diodes (LEDs) and regular diodes. Their current-voltage (I-V) relationship is non-linear, and they conduct current only in one direction once a threshold voltage is reached.    2. Transistors: Both bipolar junction transistors (BJTs) and field-effect transistors (FETs) exhibit non-linear behavior, as their operation depends on the characteristics of the semiconductor material and external biasing.    3. Thermistors: These are temperature-dependent resistors whose resistance changes significantly with temperature, leading to a non-linear I-V curve.    4. Gas Discharge Lamps: Devices such as neon lamps and fluorescent tubes have non-linear characteristics, with their current depending on the ionization of gas, which changes with applied voltage.    5. Zener Diodes: These devices maintain a constant reverse voltage after a breakdown point and do not follow a linear I-V relationship.    6. Capacitors and Inductors: While not resistive components, these devices do not exhibit a direct proportionality between current and voltage, as their impedance varies with frequency.    7. Superconductors: Below their critical temperature, superconductors exhibit zero resistance, which does not conform to Ohm's law.    8. Non-Linear Resistors: Devices like varistors and surge protectors have a non-linear I-V relationship designed for specific applications like voltage clamping.    These devices deviate from Ohm's law due to their physical properties or the mechanisms governing their operation.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"}];